itutional development (in particular of Roman politics) as well as Cicero's perception of their political theories are scrutinized to determine the extent of Cicero's awareness of a larger pattern of political events.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Backlist eBook-Package 2001-2015z978311066303740uhttps://doi.org/10.31826/978146323575840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781463235758423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781463235758/original  a978-3-11-066303-7  Gorgias Press Backlist eBook-Package 2001-2015c2001d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK